Create the Node.js backend context once in a server-only module and reuse it across requests/jobs:

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import permissions from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: { type: "persistent", dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH ?? "./jazz-data" },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});
```

Important constraints: install `jazz-napi` as a direct dependency for Node; use a stable `dataPath` for persistent storage; use `{ type: "memory" }` only with an upstream `serverUrl`; keep `BACKEND_SECRET` and `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` server-only and never public-prefixed; call `await jazz.shutdown()` on process shutdown; explicitly wait for the needed write tier before returning success from endpoints that promise durable/server-visible writes.

Use `null`, not `undefined`, when clearing an optional column in a Jazz update. `undefined` means “leave this field unchanged”.

```ts
await db.update(app.todos, todoId, {
  projectId: null,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

If the caller only needs optimistic local UI, the `.wait(...)` can be omitted.

When query inputs are reactive, pass an accessor/function so the binding rebuilds the Jazz query when inputs change.

Svelte:

```ts
import { QuerySubscription } from "jazz-tools/svelte";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todos = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  selectedProjectId
    ? app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId }).orderBy("title", "asc")
    : undefined,
);
```

Solid:

```tsx
import { useAll } from "jazz-tools/solid";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: selectedProjectId()
    ? app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId() }).orderBy("title", "asc")
    : undefined,
}));
```

Passing an already-built query captures the current value instead of tracking later changes.

Use `db.batch(...)` for two writes that should appear optimistically in the UI together. The writes become locally visible when the batch callback commits, then settle as one direct batch.

```ts
const result = db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  batch.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});

await result.wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

Use `db.transaction(...)` when the two writes must stay staged until accepted by authority and then become globally visible together.

```ts
const result = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.accounts, fromId, { balance: fromBalance - amount });
  tx.update(app.accounts, toId, { balance: toBalance + amount });
});

await result.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Define the self-reference as an optional ref column on the same table. A `managerId` ref creates the typed forward relation `manager`.

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  employees: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
    title: s.string(),
    managerId: s.ref("employees").optional(),
  }),
};

type AppSchema = s.Schema<typeof schema>;
export const app: s.App<AppSchema> = s.defineApp(schema);

export type Employee = s.RowOf<typeof app.employees>;
```

To query employees with their manager, use `include({ manager: true })`.

Use a timestamp/date column for the event time, an inline binary column for the small fingerprint, and a ref column for the project relation.

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  projects: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
  }),
  events: s.table({
    occurredAt: s.date(),
    fingerprint: s.bytes(),
    projectId: s.ref("projects"),
  }),
};

type AppSchema = s.Schema<typeof schema>;
export const app: s.App<AppSchema> = s.defineApp(schema);
```

Keep the fingerprint inline because it is small and should always load with the row; use Jazz file/blob storage only for large or separately loaded binary data.

Create the file with an edge write tier, then only create/report the parent upload after both the chunks/file row and parent row have settled at edge:

```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });

const upload = await db
  .insert(app.uploads, {
    owner_id: session.user_id,
    label,
    fileId: file.id,
  })
  .wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

On download, request the tier that represents success for the product and handle incomplete local data separately from a missing file:

```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  return URL.createObjectURL(blob);
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof IncompleteFileDataError) {
    return { state: "incomplete", reason: error.reason };
  }
  if (error instanceof FileNotFoundError) {
    return { state: "missing" };
  }
  throw error;
}
```

Revoke browser object URLs when the blob changes and on component cleanup.

Delete while the parent relationship still exists, because inherited file and part delete permissions depend on it. Load the upload, load its file, delete all parts, delete the file row, then delete the parent upload:

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  }
  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}

db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```

Do not delete the parent first. Until automatic cascade cleanup exists, that can remove the inherited authorisation path before the file rows are cleaned up, leaving orphaned chunks.

Use a real local sync topology and make row-order irrelevant by normalising on a stable key before asserting. Write with one client, wait for edge durability, then poll the second client until it observes all rows.

```ts
it("syncs several rows without depending on query order", async () => {
  const server = await startLocalJazzServer({ inMemory: true });
  const clients: Db[] = [];

  try {
    const alice = await createDb({
      appId: server.appId,
      serverUrl: server.url,
      adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
      driver: { type: "memory" },
    });
    const bob = await createDb({
      appId: server.appId,
      serverUrl: server.url,
      adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
      driver: { type: "memory" },
    });
    clients.push(alice, bob);

    await Promise.all([
      alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "B", done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
      alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "A", done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
      alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "C", done: true }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
    ]);

    await vi.waitFor(async () => {
      const rows = await bob.all(app.todos, { tier: "edge" });
      const byTitle = Object.fromEntries(
        rows.map((row) => [row.title, { title: row.title, done: row.done }]),
      );

      expect(byTitle).toEqual({
        A: { title: "A", done: false },
        B: { title: "B", done: false },
        C: { title: "C", done: true },
      });
    });
  } finally {
    await Promise.all(clients.map((client) => client.shutdown()));
    await server.stop();
  }
});
```

If the schema supports explicit ordering and order is part of the behaviour, add an order clause instead. Otherwise, normalising results avoids a flaky test that accidentally asserts transport or query iteration order.

Use `createPolicyTestApp` so the test exercises the public permission surface. Assert denied writes with `expectDenied`, and denied reads as an empty result rather than an exception.

```ts
it("denies Bob read and write access to Alice's row", async () => {
  const testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);

  try {
    const alice = testApp.as({
      user_id: "alice",
      claims: {},
      authMode: "local-first",
    });
    const bob = testApp.as({
      user_id: "bob",
      claims: {},
      authMode: "local-first",
    });

    const created = alice.insert(app.todos, {
      title: "Alice private row",
      done: false,
    }).value;

    alice.expectAllowed((db) =>
      db.update(app.todos, created.id, { title: "Alice can edit" }),
    );

    bob.expectDenied((db) =>
      db.update(app.todos, created.id, { title: "Bob cannot edit" }),
    );

    await expect(
      bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: created.id })),
    ).resolves.toEqual([]);
  } finally {
    await testApp.shutdown();
  }
});
```

This covers both halves of the policy contract: Bob cannot mutate Alice's row, and Bob's read query filters the row out.
